SIMPLE: lightly
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Lightly
<hw>Light"ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>With little weight;
with little force; <as>as, to tread <ex>lightly</ex>; to press
<ex>lightly</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Yet shall thy grave with rising flowers be drest,⟦br⟧
And the green turf lie <qex>lightly</qex> on thy breast.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Him thus intent Ithuriel with his spear⟦br⟧
Touched <qex>lightly</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Swiftly; nimbly; with agility.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So mikle was that barge, it might not <qex>lightly</qex> sail.</q>
<rj><qau>R. of Brunne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Watch what thou seest and <qex>lightly</qex> bring me word.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Without deep impression.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The soft ideas of the cheerful note,⟦br⟧
<qex>Lightly</qex> received, were easily forgot.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>In a small degree; slightly; not severely.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>At the first he <qex>lightly</qex> afflicted the land of Zebulun .
. . and afterward did more grievously afflict her.</q> <rj><qau>Is. ix.
1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>With little effort or difficulty; easily;
readily.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That <qex>lightly</qex> come, shall <qex>lightly</qex> go.</q>
<rj><qau>Old Proverb.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They come <qex>lightly</qex> by the malt, and need not spare
it.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Without reason, or for reasons of little
weight.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Flatter not the rich, neither do thou willingly or
<qex>lightly</qex> appear before great personages.</q> <rj><qau>Jer.
Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Commonly; usually.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Bp. Fisher.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The great thieves of a state are <qex>lightly</qex> the officers
of the crown.</q> <rj><qau>B. Jonson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Without dejection; cheerfully.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Seeming
to bear it <xex>lightly</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>Without heed or care; with levity; gayly;
airily.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Matrimony . . . is not by any to be enterprised, nor taken in
hand, unadvisedly, <qex>lightly</qex>, or wantonly.</q> <rj><qau>Book of
Common Prayer [Eng. Ed.].</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>Not chastely; wantonly.</def>
<rj><au>Swift.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lightman</ent>⟦br⟧
